import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static boolean canDivideIntoPairs(int[] nums) {
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            if (map.containsKey(num)) {
                map.put(num, map.get(num) + 1);
            } else {
                map.put(num, 1);
            }
        }

        for (int num : nums) {
            if (map.get(num) == 1) {
                return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {3, 2, 3, 2, 2, 2};
        System.out.println(canDivideIntoPairs(nums));  // prints: true

        int[] nums2 = {1, 2, 3, 4};
        System.out.println(canDivideIntoPairs(nums2));  // prints: false
    }
}
```

In the function `canDivideIntoPairs`, we first create a HashMap to store the count of each number in the array. Then we iterate over the array again to check if a number has a count of 1, in which case the number should be part of a pair and we return false.

Finally, we return true if we have not found any numbers that appear only once. 

This function works because in the second case, we are trying to divide the numbers into 2 pairs where each pair has the same number. In this case, we cannot do this because each number appears only once. Therefore, we return false.
